<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create Vehicle Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Spawns a vehicle at the Event Point position, including civilian cars, taxis, police vehicles, vans, ambulances, SUVs, and helicopter-related mission vehicles.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Create Vehicle Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Create Vehicle</Bold> Event Point creates a vehicle at the selected Event Point
        position. This can be used to place a player-drivable car, a locked mission vehicle, a patrol
        vehicle, a police vehicle, an ambulance, a van, an SUV, or a helicopter-style mission object.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The main things you control are the vehicle type, where it spawns, whether it is usable by
        the player, whether it requires a key, and whether it should perform special behaviour such
        as patrol or helicopter tracking.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_vehicle_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Simple summary:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Create Vehicle places one vehicle at the Event Point position. Vehicle behaviour depends on the selected vehicle type,
                    behaviour mode, key requirement, and any linked driver or Target EP setup.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adding a Create Vehicle Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To add a vehicle, click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel, select
        <Bold>Create Vehicle</Bold> from the Event Point type list, and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The <Bold>Edit EventPoint</Bold> window opens with the normal common properties and the
        Create Vehicle-specific settings.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_vehicle_add_type.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Create Vehicle uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point
        type, letter group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The <Bold>position</Bold> controls where the vehicle spawns. The <Bold>facing direction</Bold>
        controls the direction the vehicle faces when it appears.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_vehicle_common_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold> to place the vehicle in the viewport. Vehicles should
        normally be placed on a road, driveway, parking area, open yard, or other flat place where
        the game can spawn them cleanly.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Avoid placing vehicles inside buildings, inside other objects, too close to walls, or in
        places where the player or driver AI cannot reasonably reach them.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Facing Direction
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Select the Event Point and rotate the orange facing handle if the vehicle should face a
        specific direction. This is especially important for player vehicles, patrol vehicles, and
        parked cars that should line up with roads or parking spaces.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_vehicle_position_facing.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Vehicle Type
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Type</Bold> field controls which vehicle is spawned at the Event Point position.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_vehicle_type_dropdown.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Car / Civilian Sedan</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A standard civilian car. Useful for general player vehicles, parked cars, traffic scenes, or
        mission escape vehicles.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Van / Civilian Van</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A civilian van. Useful for service vehicles, industrial areas, delivery scenes, or mission
        transport setups.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Taxi</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A taxi vehicle. Useful for city scenes, roads, transport areas, or urban traffic dressing.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Helicopter</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A helicopter-style mission vehicle. The player cannot use this like a normal drivable car.
        Helicopter-specific behaviours include <Bold>Guard</Bold> and <Bold>Track</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Motorbike</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Listed as a vehicle type, but does not appear to spawn in the retail version of the game.
        Treat it as unavailable unless specifically testing engine behaviour.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Police Sedan</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A police car. Useful for police scenes, chases, patrols, and mission setups involving law
        enforcement.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Ambulance</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        An ambulance vehicle. Useful for emergency scenes, hospitals, accidents, or scripted city
        incidents.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Police SUV</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A police SUV. Useful for heavier police presence, roadblocks, chase scenes, or tactical
        police staging.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Civilian SUV</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A civilian SUV. Useful for residential, road, parking, or mission transport scenes.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Soft-Top Sedan</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A soft-top civilian-style sedan. Useful for variety in parked or usable vehicle placement.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Wildcat Van</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A Wildcat van. Useful where a more specific gang, team, or mission vehicle is required.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Retail-version note:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Motorbike appears in the vehicle list but does not appear to spawn in the retail version.
                    Helicopter exists, but the player cannot use it like a normal vehicle.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Vehicle Behaviour
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Behaviour</Bold> field controls what the vehicle is intended to do after it spawns.
        Some behaviours only make sense for certain vehicle types or require additional Event Points.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_vehicle_behaviour_dropdown.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Player Drives</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The vehicle is stationary and is intended for the player to drive. This is the typical option
        for a mission car, escape vehicle, parked vehicle, or player-usable transport.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Patrol</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        If the vehicle is occupied by a driver, it will travel to waypoints. This requires a correctly
        configured driver NPC and suitable waypoints.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical Patrol requirement:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Patrol does not work by vehicle behaviour alone. The vehicle needs an occupied driver,
                    and that driver should be configured with AI Type = Driver and Movement = Patrol Waypoints in order.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph Margin="24,6,0,0">
        For a patrol vehicle, the driver NPC should be set up with:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="40,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>AI Type:</Bold> Driver.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Movement:</Bold> Patrol Waypoints (in order).</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Appropriate waypoint Event Points for the route.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,10,0,1">Guard</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Used only for <Bold>Helicopter</Bold> vehicles. This keeps the helicopter grounded or landed
        and prevents it from moving away.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Track</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Used only for <Bold>Helicopter</Bold> vehicles. The helicopter tracks a specific Event Point
        specified in the <Bold>Target EP</Bold> field.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Target EP
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Target EP</Bold> field is used for vehicle behaviours that need a target reference.
        In this setup, it is mainly relevant to the <Bold>Track</Bold> behaviour used by helicopters.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        If a helicopter is set to <Bold>Track</Bold>, Target EP should be the Event Point number that
        the helicopter should track.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical Target EP detail:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Target EP must point to the Event Point that should be tracked.
                    Do not put the Create Vehicle Event Point's own number here unless that is deliberately the target.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_vehicle_target_ep.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Key Required
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Key Required</Bold> field controls whether the player can enter the vehicle
        immediately, needs a key, or cannot enter the vehicle at all.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_vehicle_key_required.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Unlocked</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        No key is required. The vehicle is available to the player if the vehicle type and behaviour
        allow player use. This is the most common setup for player vehicles.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Red Key</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The vehicle is locked unless the player has collected a <Bold>Key</Bold> item. This can be
        created with the <Bold>Create Item</Bold> Event Point and used to build more complex mission
        logic.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Blue Key</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Listed as an option but appears unused.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Green Key</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Listed as an option but appears unused.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Black Key</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Listed as an option but appears unused.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">White Key</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Listed as an option but appears unused.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Locked</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The car is locked and cannot be entered by the player.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Typical setup:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Player vehicles are usually Unlocked. Use Red Key or Locked only when you want mission logic to control access.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Key-Based Vehicle Logic
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Red Key</Bold> option can be used to build mission logic where the player must
        collect a key before entering a vehicle.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        A common setup is:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Player searches body/object -> finds Key -> collects Key -> Red Key vehicle can be driven
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        This usually involves combining Create Vehicle with other Event Points:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Create Vehicle</Bold> — creates the vehicle and sets Key Required to Red Key.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Create Item</Bold> — creates the Key item.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Item Hidden in Prim</Bold> or <Bold>Make Searchable</Bold> — can be used if the key is found by searching an object/body.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Optional mission triggers or messages to guide the player to the key.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This allows more complex mission sequences such as finding a key on a dead body, searching a
        vehicle, unlocking an escape car, or requiring the player to complete an objective before
        they can drive away.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Key logic warning:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Red Key vehicle access depends on the player actually collecting the Key item.
                    Make sure the Key item is created, reachable, and collectible before the player is expected to use the vehicle.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Locking Vehicles with Mission Logic
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Vehicles are commonly created as <Bold>Unlocked</Bold> when they are intended for the player.
        There is also a separate Event Point available to lock vehicles, which can be scripted behind
        mission logic.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This means you can create a vehicle normally, then use another Event Point later to lock or
        control access to it based on mission state.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Like other Event Points, Create Vehicle can spawn immediately or be placed behind mission
        logic.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Spawn Immediately
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        If the vehicle should exist as soon as the mission begins, use:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Triggered By:</Bold> None / Game Starts.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Listening Mode:</Bold> Active.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Spawn Later
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        If the vehicle should appear only after some mission condition, use a trigger such as:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> — after another Event Point has fired.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Player Enters Radius</Bold> — when the player enters a location.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Conversation Finished</Bold> — after dialogue completes.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Counter Reaches Value</Bold> — after a mission counter reaches a required value.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Timer</Bold> — after a timed delay.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_vehicle_trigger_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Practical Examples
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Simple Player Car</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create a civilian car, set Behaviour to <Bold>Player Drives</Bold>, set Key Required to
        <Bold>Unlocked</Bold>, and trigger it from the start of the mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Escape Car Requiring a Key</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create a vehicle with Key Required set to <Bold>Red Key</Bold>. Create a Key item elsewhere
        using Create Item. The player must find and collect the key before they can drive the vehicle.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Search Body, Find Key, Drive Car</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use Create Item with <Bold>Item Hidden in Prim</Bold> to hide a Key in a searchable object or
        body. Set the vehicle to require Red Key. Once the player searches and collects the key, they
        can enter the vehicle.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Patrol Vehicle</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create a vehicle with Behaviour set to <Bold>Patrol</Bold>. Add or configure a driver NPC
        with <Bold>AI Type = Driver</Bold> and <Bold>Movement = Patrol Waypoints in order</Bold>.
        Add the appropriate waypoints for the route.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Grounded Helicopter</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create a helicopter and set Behaviour to <Bold>Guard</Bold> if it should remain grounded or
        landed.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Tracking Helicopter</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Create a helicopter and set Behaviour to <Bold>Track</Bold>. Set <Bold>Target EP</Bold> to
        the Event Point the helicopter should track.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Create Vehicle Workflow
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>Create Vehicle</Bold> and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose a letter group and colour that fits your mission organisation.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold> to place the vehicle.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Rotate the facing direction so the vehicle points the correct way.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select the <Bold>Vehicle Type</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select the <Bold>Behaviour</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select the <Bold>Key Required</Bold> setting.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If using helicopter Track behaviour, set <Bold>Target EP</Bold> correctly.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If using Patrol behaviour, create/configure the driver NPC and waypoints.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trigger that spawns the vehicle.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>OK</Bold>, save, and test the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Red Key Vehicle Workflow
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create a vehicle and set <Bold>Key Required</Bold> to <Bold>Red Key</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create a <Bold>Key</Bold> item using Create Item.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place the Key visibly, or hide it using <Bold>Item Hidden in Prim</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If hidden, make sure the correct nearby object becomes searchable.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Guide the player to the key using mission messages, objectives, or search clues.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test that the vehicle cannot be entered before the key is collected.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test that the vehicle can be entered after the key is collected.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Troubleshooting
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The vehicle does not spawn</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Create Vehicle Event Point exists.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the trigger condition is firing.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test with <Bold>Triggered By: None / Game Starts</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the selected vehicle type works in the retail version.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Avoid relying on Motorbike unless specifically testing, as it does not appear to spawn in retail.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The player cannot enter the vehicle</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check the <Bold>Key Required</Bold> setting.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use <Bold>Unlocked</Bold> if no key should be required.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If using <Bold>Red Key</Bold>, confirm the player can collect the Key item.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the vehicle type is player-usable. Helicopter is not player-usable.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the vehicle is not spawned inside geometry or blocked by objects.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Patrol vehicle does not move</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm Behaviour is set to <Bold>Patrol</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the vehicle has an occupied driver.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the driver NPC uses <Bold>AI Type = Driver</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the driver movement is <Bold>Patrol Waypoints in order</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm waypoint Event Points exist and are reachable.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Helicopter does not track correctly</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the vehicle type is <Bold>Helicopter</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm Behaviour is set to <Bold>Track</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm <Bold>Target EP</Bold> points to the Event Point that should be tracked.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final note:</Run>
                <Run>
                    For most player vehicles, use Player Drives and Unlocked.
                    Use Red Key, Patrol, Guard, Track, and Target EP only when the mission specifically needs that extra logic.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>